https://github.com/yoshuawuyts/futures-c:
Yes, I agree for that specific example.

My argument would be that if you have a `Vec<impl Future>` you can use `race_with_index` without having to allocate a new `Vec` to get the index.

<hr>

Here is another example (which needs to map the `Vec`, so probably not a great example):
```rust
use std::time::Duration;

use futures_concurrency::prelude::*;
use tokio::{sync::watch, time::timeout_at};

// Imagine this actually does something useful
fn watch(_id: &str) -> watch::Receiver<u64> {
    let (tx, rx) = watch::channel(0);
    tokio::task::spawn(async move {
        for i in 164.. {
            if tx.send(i).is_err() {
                break;
            }

            tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(100)).await;
        }
    });
    rx
}

async fn f(mut rxs: Vec<watch::Receiver<u64>>) -> Vec<Option<u64>> {
    let mut states = vec![None; rxs.len()];

    let timeout_instant = tokio::time::Instant::now() + Duration::from_secs(1);

    loop {
        let changed: Vec<_> = rxs
            .iter_mut()
            .enumerate()
            .map(|(i, rx)| async move {
                rx.changed().await.unwrap();
                (i, *rx.borrow_and_update())
            })
            .collect();
        match timeout_at(timeout_instant, changed.race()).await {
            Ok((i, v)) => {
                states[i] = Some(v);
            }
            Err(_) => break,
        }
    }

    states
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    const N: usize = 3;

    let rxs: Vec<_> = (0..N).map(|i| watch(&format!("id-{i}"))).collect();

    let res = f(rxs).await;

    println!("{res:?}");
}
```

https://github.com/modiimedia/arri/issue:
Just wanted to give an update on this.

Support for other HTTP libraries will come when Arri becomes transport agnostic. I've been putting a lot of time into making that happen - so it'll be sooner rather than later.

When Arri becomes transport agnostic, logic concerning the transport itself will be separated from the ArriApp in the form of "transport adapters". You would register a "TransportAdapter" for whatever transport you want to map to Arri procedures. (Ex HTTP, Websockets, TCP, etc). So basically Arri will become a Request -> Response system built on top of whatever transport you choose.

Arri will ship with a default transport adapter for both HTTP and Websockets. The HTTP adapter will use H3 under the hood like so.

```ts
// greenfield project (no pre-existing h3 app)
import { ArriApp, HttpAdapter } from '@arrirpc/server';
const app = new ArriApp();
const httpAdapter = new HttpAdapter();
app.use(httpAdapter);

// used as part of an existing h3 app
import { createApp } from 'h3';
import { ArriApp, HttpAdapter } from '@arrirpc/server';

const h3App = createApp();
const arriApp = new ArriApp();
const httpAdapter = new HttpAdapter({ app: h3App });
```

Support for other http libraries will come in the form of standalone adapters. Here's an example of what an express adapter might look like:

```ts
// greenfield project (no pre-existing express app)
import { ArriApp } from '@arrirpc/server';
import { ExpressHttpAdapter } from '@arrirpc/express-adapter';

const app = new ArriApp();
const httpAdapter = new ExpressHttpAdapter();
app.use(httpAdapter);


// used as part of an existing expressjs app
import Express from 'express';
import { ArriApp } from '@arrirpc/server';
import { ExpressHttpAdapter } from '@arrirpc/express-adapter';

const expressApp = Express();
const arriApp = new ArriApp();
const httpAdapter = new ExpressHttpAdapter({ app: expressApp });
arriApp.use(httpAdapter);
```

Similar adapters could be made for other popular http libraries (fastify, hono, etc)

