@microlith57 not sure if this is what you're talking about (maybe I misunderstood you initially), but I was thinking it could definitely be done with entity type matching.  I feel that `TriggerZone` might be a better name given you can pass it a collider and have any arbitrary number of them.  We don't need separate source/target pairs since they pretty much do the same thing.

```cs
class TriggerZone : Component {
    Action OnEnter... etc.
}
// triggered by any TEntity
class EntityTriggerZone<TEntity> : TriggerZone where TEntity : Entity { }
// triggered by any entity with TComponent
class ComponentTriggerZone<TComponent> : TriggerZone where TComponent : Component { }
// triggered by Player
class PlayerTriggerZone : EntityTriggerZone<Player> { }
// triggered by TheoCrystal, Glider, etc.
class HoldableTriggerZone : ComponentTriggerZone<Holdable> { }
```

For an entity that acts as the "target" (such as a spring, refill, etc.)
```cs
// a better version of PlayerCollider
mySpring.Add(new PlayerTriggerZone(optionalCollider));
// a better version of HoldableCollider
mySpring.Add(new HoldableTriggerZone(optionalCollider));
```

For an entity that acts as the "source" (such as player, puffer, etc.)
```cs
// if for some reason you wanted the player to enter/stay/leave anything with a Sprite
player.Add(new ComponentTriggerZone<Sprite>(optionalCollider));
// if for some reason you wanted the puffer to enter/stay/leave any subclass of Spikes
puffer.Add(new EntityTriggerZone<Spikes>(optionalCollider));
```

We would assume the `TriggerZone` collisions/triggering is done in `TriggerZone.Update`, which means that for any `TriggerZone`s added directly to the `Player` entity, they would lag one frame behind calls to `PlayerListener` and `Trigger`s since player movement happens after `base.Update()`.  I believe the same applies to `Puffer`, `TheoCrystal`, and `Glider`.  Not sure how we would handle this.

