Hi @ShyshkovOleg,
The issues you are facing are due to how FormArray handles patchValue and updateValue.

1.patchValue: This method is designed to update the values of existing controls in the array. Since you initialized the array as empty ([]), patchValue has no controls to update and ignores the provided values.

2.updateValue: When updateValue receives a list longer than the current array, it automatically adds new controls. However, because it doesn't know the schema of your form (validators, default values, etc.), it creates simple FormControl instances containing the Map data, rather than FormGroup instances.

◦The error FormControlNotFoundException occurs because the UI tries to access a child property (name) on what it expects to be a FormGroup, but is actually a FormControl holding the Map.
To fix this, you should manually create the FormGroup instances and add them to the array.
Here is the corrected usage:

```dart
  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState(); // Best practice to call super first

    final data = [
      {'name': "option #1", 'value': '#1 value'},
      {'name': "option #2", 'value': '#2 value'}
    ];

    // Clear the array if you want to replace existing items
    optionsFormArray.clear();

    // Iterate and add FormGroups explicitly
    optionsFormArray.addAll(
      data.map((e) => FormGroup({
        'name': FormControl<String>(value: e['name']),
        'value': FormControl<String>(value: e['value']),
      })).toList()
    );
  }
```

Regarding your second question: "could I use FormControl instead of FormControlName..."
Yes, absolutely. If you have a reference to the FormControl instance, you can pass it directly to the formControl property of the widget instead of using formControlName.
Example:

```dart
ReactiveFormArray(
  formArray: optionsFormArray,
  builder: (context, formArray, child) {
    return Column(
      children: [
        for (int i = 0; i < formArray.controls.length; i++)
          Builder(
            builder: (context) {
              // Cast the control to FormGroup to access its children
              final group = formArray.control(i.toString()) as FormGroup;
              return Column(
                children: [
                  ReactiveTextField(
                    formControl: group.control('name') as FormControl,
                  ),
                  ReactiveTextField(
                    formControl: group.control('value') as FormControl,
                  ),
                ],
              );
            }
          ),
      ],
    );
  },
),
```

